<HEADLINE>
<P>
VIDEO DISCOVERY: MORE VIDEOS: 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE FLAGG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The Crimson Pirate" (1952), directed by Robert Siodmak. 104 minutes. No 
rating. A spoof of all those Errol Flynn pirate movies. 
</P>
<P>
The pirates say "Arrrgh!" a lot and tend to get their peg-legs stuck in the 
grills over the hatches. And this time it's Burt Lancaster who gets to be 
gallant as hell. 
</P>
<P>
"The Third Man" (1949), directed by Carol Reed. 100 minutes. No rating. An 
American comes to postwar Vienna to discover a friend has been murdered, and he 
winds up learning a little about love and loyalty -- too late, alas, to help 
himself. With Joseph Cotten, Orson Welles, a script by Graham Greene that is a 
marvel of wit and intelligence, and some great zither music. MIKE FLAGG 
</P>
</TEXT>
