</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL REPORT; 
</P>
<P>
WEEKDAY UPDATE; 
</P>
<P>
UCLA; 
</P>
<P>
FOLKS LOOK TO LAST PAGE IN PHONE BOOK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What's in a name? Plenty, if you happen to be Roman Zubinsky Phifer, UCLA's 
outside linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
Phifer said he believed for several years that his middle name was given to him 
because his father had a wartime buddy in Germany named Zubinsky. 
</P>
<P>
"I didn't learn until last year from my mother that they got the name Zubinsky 
out of a phone book," Phifer said. 
</P>
<P>
As for his first name, he acknowledged that he's the namesake of Roman Gabriel, 
the former Ram and Philadelphia Eagle quarterback who grew up in North 
Carolina, as did Phifer. 
</P>
<P>
Phifer, who was suspended from school last fall for an off-campus altercation, 
had a career-high 13 tackles, including three behind the line of scrimmage, in 
the 34-14 loss to Oklahoma Saturday. MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</TEXT>
