<HEADLINE>
<P>
19TH-CENTURY SAILING SHIP REPLICA TO BE OPEN FOR TOURS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A full-scale replica of a 19th-Century sailing ship, complete with wooden 
masts, will dock at the Channel Islands Harbor on Saturday as part of the 
harbor's 25th anniversary celebration. 
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Ventura County Maritime Museum, the $450,000 ship Pilgrim will 
be docked behind the Whale's Tail Restaurant and will be available for public 
tours until next Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
As part of the festivities, the ship will be the site of the theatrical version 
of Richard Henry Dana's epic "Two Years Before the Mast." The one-act, one-man 
show, which will run Saturday and Sunday, depicts Dana's experiences as a 
sailor aboard the Pilgrim in 1835. 
</P>
<P>
Guided tours of the ship and the smaller ship Witch of Wood will be offered 
from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Sunday through Thursday. The cost is $3, $1.50 for 
children 12 and under. 
</P>
<P>
The original Pilgrim was built in Medford, Mass., in 1825 at a cost of $50,000 
and was lost 21 years later in a fire at sea. The Pilgrim's home dock is Dana 
Point Harbor, where it acts as a classroom for the Orange County Maritime 
Institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
