<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOW TO JOIN A SOFTBALL LEAGUE IN ORANGE COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELENA BRUNET 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last call to sign up for the fall season of softball leagues in some cities in 
Orange County: Fields are already reserved, and teams are playing in the 
majority of cities. 
</P>
<P>
In Santa Ana, the team must be registered with the city. Only men's and co-ed 
leagues are offered. (Co-ed teams require five men and five women players.) The 
level of play must be specified (A, B, C or D with A the most proficient) as 
must the type of game: men's or co-ed fast or slow pitch. The application must 
specify preferences for playing field, day and time (first through sixth 
choices). The name of the team and the names and addresses of the players must 
be provided. The fast-pitch league requires nine players on a team; the 
slow-pitch league requires 10. In the last few years in Santa Ana, the number 
of softball teams per season has averaged more than 600 (there are four 
seasons), according to Randy Hoopii, recreation program coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
In the city of La Habra, teams must fill out a registration form and pay a fee 
to join the men's or co-ed leagues. In the two remaining days of registration, 
the community services department will take applications as long as slots are 
available. 
</P>
<P>
In San Juan Capistrano, sign-ups are taking place right now and will continue 
through tomorrow. Only men's softball is offered for the fall season; co-ed 
teams begin in the summer. 
</P>
<P>
The softball league in Laguna Beach accepts only locals. Players must live 
within the Laguna Beach Unified School District boundaries or have proof of 
employment within the city limits. There are men's and women's leagues but no 
co-ed league. Prices and leagues are designated by the circumference of the 
softball used, 12- or 16-inch. 
</P>
<P>
A point system is utilized in cities such as Orange and Santa Ana to determine 
registration priority. Points are awarded to teams with members who are 
residents. In Santa Ana one point is also awarded to a team that played during 
the previous season or to a team from a workplace located in the city. If too 
many teams sign up and some must be eliminated, teams with the most points get 
top priority. The system also encourages teams to seek out their neighbors to 
fill their rosters. Non-residents are not excluded, but they get no points. 
</P>
<P>
In Seal Beach, points are awarded only to teams that have played previously in 
the league. 
</P>
<P>
In Mission Viejo, leagues (organized by the Saddleback Valley Recreation 
Services) are nearly full, but an independent softball league still has space 
in its men's C and D leagues, which play on Sunday nights. 
</P>
<P>
The deadline has passed for leagues in Anaheim, Buena Park, Costa Mesa, 
Cypress, Fountain Valley, Fullerton, Garden Grove, Huntington Beach, Irvine, La 
Palma, Los Alamitos, Newport Beach, Placentia, Tustin, Westminster, Yorba 
Linda, and leagues are already in play. Dana Point is connected with Capistrano 
Bay Parks and Recreation. The city of Brea will not have a league until the 
spring. None exists in Villa Park. 
</P>
<P>
Here are the costs and other information about leagues still open this fall: 
</P>
<P>
